  >>>
    Living things are made up of atoms, but these atoms aren’t just floating around individually. They are usually interacting with other atoms (or groups of atoms). They interact by forming a __chemical bond__ with each other. The reason they do that is because  atoms are trying to reach a more stable (lowest-energy) state that they can.
    Elements are more stable when their outermost shell is filled with electrons according to the octet rule. However not all elements have enough electrons to fill their outermost shells, so atoms form chemical bonds with other atoms (or group of atoms) either by gaining, losing or sharing electrons with them to attain a stable electron configuration. The new grouping is typically more stable—less likely to react again—than its component atoms were when they were separate.
    When two or more atoms chemically bond with each other, the resultant chemical structure is a __molecule__- the smallest part of the compound that holds the chemical identity of that compound. The bonded atoms may be of the same element, as in the case of H2, which is called molecular hydrogen or hydrogen gas.
    When a molecule is made up of two or more atoms of different elements, it is called a __chemical compound.__ Ex:-
    * A unit of water, or H2O, is a compound, consisting of two hydrogen atoms and one oxygen atom.
    * A single molecule of the gas methane, or CH4 is also a compound.
    A __bond__ is a weak or strong electrical attraction that holds atoms together. Three types of chemical bonds are important in human physiology, because they hold together substances that are used by the body for critical aspects of homeostasis, signaling, and energy production, to name just a few important processes. These are: __Ionic Bonds__, __Covalent Bonds__ and __Hydrogen Bonds__



