    / Bond Length
    /// Bond Length is the average distance between nuclei of two bonded atoms in a molecule.
    model bondlength
      >>>
        The covalent bond in the hydrogen molecule (H2) has a certain length (measured as the distance between the two nuclei), which is 7.4 × 10−11 m.
        This particular bond length shows a balance between several forces:
        * Attractions between oppositely charged electrons and nuclei
        * Repulsion between two negatively charged electrons
        * Repulsion between two positively charged nuclei.
        If two nuclei are closer to each other, they would repel each other more strongly; if the nuclei are farther away, there would be less attraction.
        The bond length decreases, as the number of covalent bonds between two atoms increases. With more electrons shared between the two nuclei, can get the nuclei closer together till the repulsion between nuclei is strong enough to balance the attraction.

    / Electronegativity and Bond Polarity
    /// Bond polarity is the separation of electric charge along a bond. Electronegativity measures a particular atom's attraction for electrons.
    model bondpolarity
      >>>
        The electrons in a covalent bond are not always shared equally by the two bonded atoms, unless both atoms are of the same elements. If bonded atoms are of different elements, there will always be one atom strongly attracting the electrons than the other atom. The occurrence of such imbalance results in the buildup of some negative charge on one side of the bond and some positive charge on the other side of the bond.
        A covalent bond that has an unequal sharing of electrons, is called a __polar covalent bond__. A covalent bond that has an equal sharing of electrons is called a __nonpolar covalent bond__.
        The degree of polarity varies a lot in a covalent bond. Some bonds between different elements have minimal polarity, while others have strong polarity. In Ionic bonds, electrons are transferred rather than shared, thus considered the ultimate in polarity.
        To measure the relative polarity of a covalent bond, chemists use {electronegative electronegativity} (Measure of tendency of an atom to attract a shared pair of electrons towards itself). The difference in electronegativity of two bonding atoms determines the polarity of a covalent bond. More the difference in electronegativities, more the imbalance of bonded electrons between the atoms. Although there are no definite rules, the general rule is
        * The bond is considered nonpolar, if the difference in electronegativities is less than about 0.4.
        * The bond is considered polar, if the difference is greater than 0.4.
        * The bond is considred ionic rather than covalent, if the difference in electronegativities is large (in general, greater than 1.8)
        * The bond is nonpolar covalent, if electronegativity difference is zero.



    / Polar Covalent Bond
    /// A covalent bond that has an unequal sharing of electrons, is called a polar covalent bond.
    model polar
      >>>
        In a polar covalent bond, the electrons are unequally shared by the atoms and are attracted more to one nucleus than the other. The atom that more strongly attracts the bonding electron pair is slightly more negative, while the other atom is slightly more positive. The larger the difference in the electronegativities, the more negative and positive the atoms become. The presence of a polar covalent bond in a molecule can have some pretty dramatic effects on the properties of a molecule.
        In polar covalent bond, the molecule has a positive end and a negative end, therefore it can attract the part of another molecule with the opposite charge.
        The most familiar example of a polar molecule is water. The molecule has three parts: one atom of oxygen, the nucleus of which contains eight protons, and two hydrogen atoms, whose nuclei each contain only one proton. Because every proton exerts an identical positive charge, a nucleus that contains eight protons exerts a charge eight times greater than a nucleus that contains one proton. This means that the negatively charged electrons present in the water molecule are more strongly attracted to the oxygen nucleus than to the hydrogen nuclei. Each hydrogen atom’s single negative electron therefore migrates toward the oxygen atom, making the oxygen end of their bond slightly more negative than the hydrogen end of their bond.
        What is true for the bonds is true for the water molecule as a whole; that is, the oxygen region has a slightly negative charge and the regions of the hydrogen atoms have a slightly positive charge. These charges are often referred to as “partial charges” because the strength of the charge is less than one full electron, as would occur in an ionic bond. As shown in figure regions of weak polarity are indicated with the Greek letter delta (δ) and a plus (+) or minus (–) sign.
        IMAGE FROM TEXTBOOK OPEN STAX
        Even though a single water molecule is unimaginably tiny, it has mass, and the opposing electrical charges on the molecule pull that mass in such a way that it creates a shape somewhat like a triangular tent. This dipole, with the positive charges at one end formed by the hydrogen atoms at the “bottom” of the tent and the negative charge at the opposite end (the oxygen atom at the “top” of the tent) makes the charged regions highly likely to interact with charged regions of other polar molecules. For human physiology, the resulting bond is one of the most important formed by water—the hydrogen bond.
        Since macromolecules often have atoms within them that differ in electronegativity, polar bonds are often present in organic molecules.


