  /// Electronegativity is a measure of tendency of an atom to attract a shared pair of electrons towards itself.
  model electronegative
    >>>
      An atom's electronegativity is affected by both its atomic number and the distance at which its valence electrons reside from the charged nucleus.
      On the most basic level, electronegativity is determined by factors like :
      * the nuclear charge (the more protons an atom has, the more "pull" it will have on electrons)
      * the number/location of other electrons present in the atomic shells (the more electrons an atom has, the valence electrons will be further away from the nucleus, and as a result they will experience less positive charge)— because of their increased distance from the nucleus,and because the other electrons in the lower energy core orbitals will act to shield the valence electrons from the positively charged nucleus.
      Electronegativities give information about what will happen to the bonding pair of electrons when two atoms bond.
      * If atoms bonded together have the __same__ electronegativity, the shared electrons will be equally shared. Take the example of an O2 molecule, where both atoms have the same electronegativity. The electrons in this bond are equally shared between the two oxygen atoms.
      * If one atom is __more__ electronegative, the electrons of the bond are more attracted to that atom. Ex- Hydrogen chloride (HCl): Hydrogen has an electronegativity of 2.1, and chlorine has an electronegativity of 3.0. The shared electron pair of HCl shifts more toward the chlorine atom due to its larger electronegativity value.
      * If one atom is __overwhelmingly more__ electronegative than the other atom (difference in electronegativity is large enough), the electrons will not be shared. Ex- Sodium chloride (NaCl) is ionically bonded where an electron from sodium (electronegativity 1.0) has been transferred to chlorine (electronegativity 3.0). Electronegativity difference is 2.0 (3.0 – 1.0) which makes the bond between the two atoms very, very polar.
      Electronegativity is an important quantity in determining the nature of bonds between elements and will be considered as the main factor in chemical bonding. As it is usually calculated, electronegativity is not a property of an atom alone, but rather a property of an atom in a molecule. Properties of a free atom include ionization energy and electron affinity. It is to be expected that the electronegativity of an element will vary with its chemical environment, but it is usually considered to be a transferable property, that is to say that similar values will be valid in a variety of situations.
      _Ex- The most electronegative element on the periodic table is fluorine (3.98). The least electronegative element is cesium (0.79). The opposite of electronegativity is electropositivity, so you could simply say cesium is the most electropositive element._
      <br>
      ## Electronegativity as a {elements.Atoms.periodictable Periodic Table} Trend
      There are various numerical scales for rating electronegativity. One of the most popular is the Pauling scale.
      Electronegativity generally increases on passing from left to right across a period because the increased number of nucleus charge strongly attracts the bonding pair of electrons. The noble gases tend to be exceptions to this trend.
      It generally decreases as you go down a group because the bonding pair of valence electrons is increasingly distant from the nucleus.
      Electronegativity and ionization energy  shows similar periodic table trend. Generally, elements having low ionization energies tend to have low electronegativities i.e The nuclei of these atoms don't apply a strong pull on electrons.
      <hr>
      The degree of polarity between bonds varies widely. Therefore we use Electronegativity to measure the relative polarity of a bond.
